    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "22340f361013d6cb",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "22340f361013d6cb",
        "text": "Each of [[Niklas Luhmann]]'s texts makes a contribution to a theory of society. Unlike special sociologies, this general theory must conceive of itself as part of its subject area. Thus, on the one hand, it must sociologically describe a society that produces a sociology capable of presenting a theory of that society; and, on the other hand, it must be prepared for the fact that sociology, with its description of society, changes the object receiving this description. The relation is to be thought circularly. The book title of Luhmann's last major work, *Die Gesellschaft der Gesellschaft* (The Society of Society), quite deliberately exhibits this circularity, but in substance, the first major work, *Soziale Systeme. Grundriß einer allgemeinen Theorie*, says nothing else: Theories with a claim to universality are easily recognized by the fact that they themselves appear as their own object. Universality of the subject areas in the sense that as a sociological theory it treats everything social and not only sections (such as stratification and mobility, characteristics of modern society, patterns of interaction, etc.)."
