      "id": "89f7b49c65a5d08d",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "89f7b49c65a5d08d",
        "text": "The book title of Luhmann's last major work, *Die Gesellschaft der Gesellschaft* (The Society of Society), quite deliberately flaunts this circularity, but at its core the first major work, *Soziale Systeme. Grundriß einer allgemeinen Theorie*, says nothing else: theories with claims to universality are easily recognized by the fact that they themselves appear as their own subject matter. Universality of subject matter in the sense that, as a sociological theory, it deals with everything social and not just sub-areas (such as stratification and mobility, features of modern society, patterns of interaction, etc.).\n"
      },
      "date": 1664393134588
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "03ec1b661a598a5a",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "03ec1b661a598a5a",
        "text": "And also in the magnificent, recently published, comprehensive work The Systems Theory of Society from his estate, Luhmann points out that the claim to a \"general theory of social systems\" implies precisely that \"sociology can also conceive of itself as a subsystem of society\" (Luhmann 2017, p. 12 f.). This is consequential for a systems-theoretical conception of the media, which grasps mass media as a \"condition of the possibility of modern society\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 883 f.) and thus at the same time counts among the conditions of possibility of the systems theory of society."
      },
      "after": "89f7b49c65a5d08d",
      "date": 1664393135440
