      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "f6d0b940fc702742",
        "text": "All three of these works are certainly not \"key works of media studies,\" but for the topic of media, two things emerge from the basic theoretical arrangement: 1) Media, insofar as they are to be counted as part of the social, must be dealt with by systems theory. 2) Insofar as media (language, writing, letterpress, mass media, cf. Luhmann 2017, p. 883) belong to the preconditions of society that sociology describes, the relations are also to be 'thought circularly' in this case.\n"
      },
      "date": 1664393332565
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "f2b9142f37b0ad09",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "f2b9142f37b0ad09",
        "text": "Having said this much about Luhmann's sociology of systems, one can expect that The Reality of Mass Media also follows the theoretical structure of the main works and treats mass media as an object which, firstly, belongs 'to the social' and which, secondly, has a circular relationship with its sociological description. One is not disappointed: \"Inevitably, any description of our society must include these means (and to that extent: its own means) and their relation to itself,\" Luhmann (1997, p. 1097) demands. Mass media thus only become an object of sociology at all insofar as they belong to the object area as something social - in Luhmann's case, therefore, as an \"institution of society\" that \"make[s] use of technical means of reproduction for the dissemination of communication\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 10), so that \"no interaction among those present can take place between sender and receiver,\" and because of this technically conditioned \"interruption of direct contact,\" the mass media's \"readiness to broadcast and interest in broadcasting [...] cannot be centrally coordinated\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 11 f.). The mass media communicate information that is understood however by the one who \"sees, hears, reads\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 14). They offer - without being able to precisely determine the \"currently participating circle of addressees\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 14) \"in contrast to an interaction among those present\" - selection offers of which they can only assume that they will also be accepted. The mass media therefore make do with \"assumptions about reasonableness and acceptance\" (1997, p. 12), but the readers, listeners, and viewers also form expectations about which offer they can expect when and from which medium. \"Accordingly, the knowledge conveyed by the mass media slides over minds without looking inside them. It creates no certainty about what individuals now really mean or prefer\" (Luhmann 2017, p. 893). The technical separation of senders and receivers nonetheless enables a buildup of expectations and expectations of expectations on both sides (i.e., ego's expectation of what alter expects ego to expect). Luhmann has found the beautiful image of a mirror for this, where the back is also mirrored: Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
