    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "5beb14aea09f5508",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "5beb14aea09f5508",
        "text": "From wherever you look in this mirror: One sees oneself and others. And also an observer, who would come to it, would also see himself in this mirror, as he observes others to observe himself in the mirror. Here, too, the relations are to be 'thought circularly'. And just as society produces a sociology that describes a society that conceives a sociology of society, which can then be called The Society of Society, so the title The Reality of Mass Media can be understood as indicating that the reality of mass media is a reality produced in our society, a reality produced in society and by the social operations of society itself - a reality that is no more and no less than an 'internal correlate of system operations (Luhmann 1996, p. 19). In principle, this applies to any system that is able to distinguish self-reference from external reference and form assumptions about itself and its environment. Insofar as mass media are part of the \"condition of the possibility of modern society\" (Luhmann 2017, p. 883 f.), however, the particular question arises here to what extent the reality of society must be understood as the reality of mass media in the sense of \"what appears as reality for them or through them for others\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 14, orig. cit.)."
      },
