    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "0e4a632958acc1aa",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "0e4a632958acc1aa",
        "text": "Okay, from where else, one might think today, but in 1994 a different doctrine would have been common: Namely, that the mass media \"misrepresent\", \"distort\" or \"alienate\" knowledge about the world and society, as Richard David Precht in his review of the booklet for DIE ZEIT (November 22, 1996) sums up the common sense with which Luhmann \"provocatively\" broke. Precht is right about this. According to Luhmann, the mass media \"distortion of communication\" (1971b, p. 121; cf. Habermas 1990, p. 28) feared and criticized by Jürgen Habermas, for instance, to cite the most prominent example, is not a problem at all, because there is only \"little point in asking whether and how the mass media reproduce an existing reality in a distorted way; they produce a description of reality, a construction of the world, and that is the reality on which society orients itself\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 1102). \"Distortion of communication\"? Spare me. The good question \"is not: How do the mass media distort reality by the way they present it?\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 20). You can't dump one of your most famous and renowned colleagues any cooler than that; Luhmann's italics make the point even more special."
      },
      "after": "98af67f86f5a46de",
      "date": 1664400163299
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "0e4a632958acc1aa",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "0e4a632958acc1aa",
        "text": "Okay, from where else, one might think today, but in 1994 a different doctrine would have been common: Namely, that the mass media \"misrepresent\", \"distort\" or \"alienate\" knowledge about the world and society, as Richard David Precht in his review of the booklet for DIE ZEIT (November 22, 1996) sums up the common sense with which Luhmann \"provocatively\" broke. Precht is right about this. According to Luhmann, the mass media \"distortion of communication\" (1971b, p. 121; cf. Habermas 1990, p. 28) feared and criticized by Jürgen Habermas, for instance, to cite the most prominent example, is not a problem at all, because there is only \"little point in asking whether and how the mass media reproduce an existing reality in a distorted way; they produce a description of reality, a construction of the world, and that is the reality on which society orients itself\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 1102). \"Distortion of communication\"? Spare me. The good question \"is not: How do the mass media distort reality by the way they present it?\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 20). You can't dump one of your most famous and renowned colleagues any cooler than that; Luhmann's italics make the point even more special.\n"
