      "type": "add",
      "id": "f051d35eb1924795",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "f051d35eb1924795",
        "text": "So sociologists do not observe society (and its media) 'from the outside', 'unmediated' or otherwise privileged, but as persons whose reality is also (or also) a reality which appears as reality for them through the mass media. If one now tried to reassure oneself by saying that this is probably \"only\" true for society, which has always been described \"subjectively\" in this or another way, but not for nature, whose reality is not constructed, but really is the way it is, then one is immediately disappointed; an imposition for all those who believe that they have to \"separate between the pure social force and the pure natural mechanism [...]\" (Latour 1998, p. 44): \"This applies not only to our knowledge of society and history, but also to our knowledge of nature. What we know about the stratosphere is like what Plato knows about Atlantis: one has heard about it\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 9)."
