      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "3038f30e88cc43fd",
        "text": "This was so provocative and at the same time so stimulating in the early 1990s that it \"immediately made the rounds\" in the relevant theoretical circles (Weischenberg 2014, p. 343). And again, this presupposes mass media and their \"popularization\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 20), which in turn implies that Luhmann's contribution is also suitable as a mass media topic, which depends less on scientific criteria one might apply to a systems sociology paper to judge its plausibility and assess its value to the field, but mainly on, whether, in the case of this small but rather complicated and idiosyncratically formulated booklet - one of hundreds of thousands of books published in 1996, and one of an incalculable number of sociological publications - the agencies of the mass media reckon with \"Einschaltinteresse\" and therefore show a \"readiness to broadcast\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 12). This has been the case. The media reported. Nikolaus von Festenberg begins his review (Der Spiegel, 7.10.1996) thus: \"Plain, apodictic and hammer-hard it stands there, the first sentence of Niklas Luhmann's new book, which will revolutionize the discussion about the influence of press and television: 'What we know about our society, indeed about the world in which we live, we know through the mass media'\". What one needs to know about Luhmann is also known from the mass media. And also the sociologist must look into the non-transparent mirror and pay attention to who else is coming into view next to him and who is possibly observing how he is being observed. It depends on \"being currently informed\" (Luhmann 1996, p. 120): \"whoever, as a researcher, is not ahead of others in his sensitivity to problems, will constantly remain in second place, analyzing afterwards what others have thought and written\" (Luhmann 2017, p. 890). "
