      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "6865e73399135e16",
        "text": "Certainly, the West German publishing house could count on resonance in the field, guaranteed by the renowned author, whose writings had to be received. However, the publishing house does not seem to have reckoned with the mass media's interest in their sociological observations and the successful popularization of their writings. Precht states (Die Zeit, 22.11.1996): \"The new work Die Realität der Massenmedien is a sales success; so unusual, for a complicated theory book, that the publisher was not prepared for it at all at first\". The sales success could be based on the fact that already the first sentence is first of all quotable (so far almost everybody reads) and for many scientific texts (so far, as said, there are at least several thousand), which have to document the knowledge of the state of research or also readership, this quotation is already sufficient, and secondly also for the non-sociologist a useful party piece represents, whose clou then lies in rejecting theses about the manipulation of reality by the media sovereignly with the assertion that media produce this reality. In the game of Bielefeld High School versus Frankfurt School, anyone who likes can join in."
