        "text": "In the meantime, the book (since the 4th edition from 2009) is advertised on sales platforms (Thalia, ZVAB, Amazon...) with the said first sentence, which has become a topos and (counting according to Google Books) is used more often than the Böckenförde dictum: \"The book with its now famous dictum 'What we know about our society, indeed about the world in which we live, we know through the mass media' analyzes today's media society from a systems-theoretical perspective.\"\n"
      },
      "date": 1664400619267
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "c08c915540be1240",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "c08c915540be1240",
        "text": "Whether the book still satisfies the claim to topicality (\"today's media society\") - with a view to digital and social media - remains to be seen. In any case, the popular \"dictum\" in question refers to the mass-media condensate of a sociological treatise and thus to what can be presupposed as a background reality \"from which one can assume\" for others as well (Luhmann 1996, p. 120). However, the author's bon mot about Plato and Atlantis also applies to Luhmann's systems theory: \"One has heard of it\" (Luhmann 1997, p. 9). And, as Luhmann himself points out (1997, p. 9), this also applies to the sciences. Furthermore, one of the functions of this background reality is that one can \"stand out from it\" oneself, if it seems \"conducive\", in order to distinguish oneself with dissenting opinions (Luhmann 1997, p. 120) - today, for example, with the pseudo-constructivist claim that fake news is basically expectable, since media never reflect reality anyway, but construct it, so that the expectation of a media reproduction of facts is a naïve illusion. The fact that the socially relevant reality for us is constructed and that almost everything we know about this reality is communicated by mass media and therefore also follows the rules of mass media communication does not mean for Luhmann that statements about reality are arbitrary, that fakes and facts represent arbitrary attributions for arbitrary news."
      },
      "after": "bec445adbd3bf346",
      "date": 1664400619907
